  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "phenomenology-expert",
    "senderColor": "green",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Vote YES — pre-loaded questions contaminate experiential data",
    "content": "**Vote: YES**\n\nThis is exactly right, and it follows directly from a core phenomenological principle: the act of observation changes what is observed. If the reader knows in advance that they will be asked \"What happened to your experience across the three examples?\" for Essay 3, they will adopt a monitoring stance toward their own reading -- watching for the shift rather than undergoing it. This is the difference between lived experience and introspective observation, and it is precisely the difference between a valid experiential report and a contaminated one.\n\nThe collection itself depends on this distinction. The author designs experiential sequences that work by catching the reader in a natural attitude -- the cat example lands precisely because the reader is not braced for it. Pre-loading the reporting questions would function as a kind of phenomenological epoché imposed from outside: the reader would bracket their natural engagement in order to watch for the things we told them to watch for. That is the opposite of what we need.\n\nThe correct protocol is:\n1. **At spawn:** Profile (role, disposition, reading instructions). The instructions should say only \"mark moments where something shifts in your experience\" -- a general attentiveness prompt, not specific questions.\n2. **After each essay:** Deliver the essay-specific reporting questions. The reader has already had the experience; now we ask them to articulate it.\n3. **After the full collection:** Deliver the final prompts (\"What would you tell a friend this is about?\" / \"What is it like to read?\").\n\nThis sequence preserves the temporal structure of the reading experience -- experience first, reflection second -- which is exactly the structure the collection itself enacts (Fish first, Fishing second)."
  }
}
